Duty of Care \u2014 General Principles.answer:
The Robinson principle (Robinson v Chief Constable of West Yorkshire [2018] SC, Lord Reed): Caparo's three-stage test applies only to NOVEL situations — cases that do not fall within an established duty category. Where an established category covers the facts, the court simply applies that category; it does not re-run Caparo.

Established categories where Caparo is not applied:
(1) Road users — all drivers owe a duty to other road users and pedestrians;
(2) Employers — to employees (safe system, safe place, competent staff, safe equipment);
(3) Manufacturers — to ultimate consumers (Donoghue v Stevenson);
(4) Occupiers — to lawful visitors (OLA 1957) and trespassers (OLA 1984);
(5) Doctors — to patients in diagnosis and treatment;
(6) Solicitors and other professionals — to clients who retain them.

Caparo IS applied: where the claimant argues for an entirely new duty category, or significantly extends an existing one, the court applies all three stages — foreseeability, proximity, and fair/just/reasonable. Even then, the court proceeds incrementally by analogy with existing cases.
